msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "WSL specific configuration\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:43
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You will have to choose a fake domain, since it will not be accessible from outside.\n"
"For example, `ynh.wsl`. The tricky part is advertising this domain to your host.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "Alter your `C:\\Windows\\System32\\drivers\\etc\\hosts` file. You should have a line starting by `::1`, update it or add it if needed to get:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you want to create subdomains, do not forget to add them in the `hosts` file too:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "This will be the domain used by your server's users to access the **authentication portal**. You can later add other domains, and change which one is the main domain if needed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you're new to self-hosting and do not already have a domain name, we recommend using a **.nohost.me** / **.noho.st** / **.ynh.fr** (e.g. `homersimpson.nohost.me`). Provided that it's not already taken, the domain will be configured automatically and you won't need any further configuration step. Please note that the downside is that you won't have full-control over the DNS configuration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you already own a domain name, you probably want to use it here. You will later need to configure DNS records as explained [here](/admin/get_started/post_install/dns_config).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced div block (tip)
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:62
#, no-wrap
msgid "Yes, you *have to* configure a domain name. If you don't have any domain name and don't want a **.nohost.me** / **.noho.st** / **.ynh.fr** either, you can set up a dummy domain such as `yolo.test` and tweak your **local** `/etc/hosts` file such that this dummy domain [points to the appropriate IP, as explained here](/admin/tutorials/domains/dns_local_network).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:66
#, no-wrap
msgid "<FAIcon icon=\"fa-key\"/> First user"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "The first user is now created at this stage. You should pick a username and a reasonably complex password. (We cannot stress enough that the password should be **robust**!) This user will be added to the Admins group, and will therefore be able to access the user portal, the web admin interface, and connect [via **SSH**](/admin/command_line) or [**SFTP**](/admin/tutorials/filezilla). Admins will also receive emails sent to `root@yourdomain.tld` and `admin@yourdomain.tld`: these emails may be used to send technical informations or alerts. You can later add additional users, which you can also add to the Admins group.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "This user replaces the old `admin` user, which some old documentation page may still refer to. In which case: just replace `admin` with your username.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "<FAIcon icon=\"fa-stethoscope\"/> Run the initial diagnosis"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:75
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once the postinstall is done, you should be able to actually log in the web admin interface using the credentials of the first user you just created.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "The diagnosis system is meant to provide an easy way to validate that all critical aspects of your server are properly configured - and guide you in how to fix issues. The diagnosis will run twice a day and send an alert if issues are detected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced div block (tip)
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Don't run away** ! The first time you run the diagnosis, it is quite expected to see a bunch of yellow/red alerts because you typically need to [configure DNS records](/admin/get_started/post_install/dns_config) (if not using a `.nohost.me`/`noho.st`/`ynh.fr` domain), add a swapfile if not enough ram as well as [port forwarding](/admin/get_started/post_install/port_forwarding) on your home's router.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced div block (tip)
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:82
#, no-wrap
msgid "If an alert is not relevant (for example because you don't intend on using a specific feature), it is perfectly fine to flag the issue as 'ignored' by going in the webadmin > Diagnosis, and clicking the ignore button for this specifc issue.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced div block (warning)
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/_configuration.mdx:86
#, no-wrap
msgid "Especially, installations on WSL or virtual machines will likely not be reachable from outside without further network configuration on Virtualbox and your machine.\n"
msgstr ""

